  <div id="modal-appeal-decision" class="modal" hidden><div class="modal-content"><button class="modal-close" aria-label="Close modal">&times;</button><div class="modal-header"><div class="modal-header-icon">{% image "/images/three-dots-white.svg", "Icon symbolizing appealing a decision for West Virginia Democrats", { widths: [40, 80], sizes: "40px" } %}</div><h3>Procedure: Appealing a Decision</h3></div><div class="modal-body"><p class="modal-summary">Use this process to formally challenge a ruling or decision made by a WV Democratic committee, club, or convention.</p><div class="key-facts-box"><h4>Key Facts</h4><ul><li><strong>Filing Deadline:</strong> 30 days from the date of the decision.</li><li><strong>Who Can File:</strong> The party that lost the decision.</li><li><strong>Source:</strong> WVSDEC Bylaws, Art. VIII, Sec. 2-3</li></ul></div><hr class="modal-divider"><h4>Your Step-by-Step Guide</h4><ol><li><strong>Draft Your Appeal:</strong> Prepare a formal written notice. Clearly state the decision you are contesting, the date it was made, and the specific reasons for your appeal.</li><li><strong>File with the State Chair:</strong> You must <strong>submit</strong> your written notice to the WVSDEC State Chair within the 30-day deadline.</li><li><strong>Await Hearing Notice:</strong> The Board of Appeals will be called for a hearing within 30 days. You will receive at least 5 days' written notice of the hearing.</li></ol><hr class="modal-divider"><h4>What to Expect Next</h4><p>You must attend the hearing to present your case. If you fail to appear without good cause, a decision will likely be made against you. The Board's decision is final unless overturned by a 2/3 vote of the full State Executive Committee.</p></div></div></div>
  <div id="modal-contest-delegation" class="modal" hidden><div class="modal-content"><button class="modal-close" aria-label="Close modal">&times;</button><div class="modal-header"><div class="modal-header-icon">{% image "/images/three-dots-white.svg", "Icon symbolizing contesting a delegation in West Virginia", { widths: [40, 80], sizes: "40px" } %}</div><h3>Procedure: Contesting a Delegation</h3></div><div class="modal-body"><p class="modal-summary">Use this process to challenge the delegates selected at a party convention or caucus.</p><div class="key-facts-box"><h4>Key Facts</h4><ul><li><strong>Starting Point:</strong> The County Executive Committee hears the contest first.</li><li><strong>Appeal Deadline:</strong> 30 days from the County Committee's decision to appeal to the state.</li><li><strong>Source:</strong> WVSDEC Bylaws, Art. VII, Sec. 9</li></ul></div><hr class="modal-divider"><h4>Your Step-by-Step Guide</h4><ol><li><strong>File with County Committee:</strong> Immediately <strong>file your challenge</strong> with the County Executive Committee. They must meet to hear the conflict within 10 days of the mass convention.</li><li><strong>Appeal to the State (If Necessary):</strong> If you disagree with the county's decision, you have 30 days to <strong>file a written appeal</strong> with the WVSDEC State Chair.</li><li><strong>Prepare Your Packet:</strong> Your appeal should include your petition, copies of the meeting minutes, public notices, sign-in sheets, and any other evidence. Clearly state the remedy you are seeking.</li></ol><hr class="modal-divider"><h4>What to Expect Next</h4><p>The state's Board of Appeals will hear your case. The state courts also have jurisdiction to review a County Executive Committee's decision.</p></div></div></div>
  <div id="modal-remove-member" class="modal" hidden><div class="modal-content"><button class="modal-close" aria-label="Close modal">&times;</button><div class="modal-header"><div class="modal-header-icon">{% image "/images/three-dots-white.svg", "Icon symbolizing removing a committee member in West Virginia", { widths: [40, 80], sizes: "40px" } %}</div><h3>Procedure: Removing a Member for Cause</h3></div><div class="modal-body"><p class="modal-summary">This is the process for removing a member from the State Democratic Executive Committee.</p><div class="key-facts-box"><h4>Key Facts</h4><ul><li><strong>Who Can Initiate:</strong> Two or more members of the WVSDEC.</li><li><strong>Vote Needed:</strong> 3/5 of voting members.</li><li><strong>Source:</strong> WVSDEC Bylaws, Art. V, Sec. 10(b)</li></ul></div><hr class="modal-divider"><h4>Your Step-by-Step Guide</h4><ol><li><strong>Submit Affidavits:</strong> Two or more WVSDEC members must <strong>submit signed affidavits</strong> detailing the facts that constitute "good cause" <em>(e.g., bylaw violations, supporting an opponent)</em>.</li><li><strong>Ensure Notice is Sent:</strong> The member being challenged must <strong>receive written notice</strong> at least 15 days before the meeting where their removal will be considered.</li><li><strong>Attend the Hearing:</strong> The challenged member has the right to be heard. The members who submitted affidavits **must be present** for questioning.</li></ol><hr class="modal-divider"><h4>What to Expect Next</h4><p>If a 3/5 majority votes for removal, the position is declared immediately vacant and will be filled according to the bylaws.</p></div></div></div>
  <div id="modal-remove-officer" class="modal" hidden><div class="modal-content"><button class="modal-close" aria-label="Close modal">&times;</button><div class="modal-header"><div class="modal-header-icon">{% image "/images/three-dots-white.svg", "Icon symbolizing removing an officer in West Virginia", { widths: [40, 80], sizes: "40px" } %}</div><h3>Procedure: Removing an Officer from Office</h3></div><div class="modal-body"><p class="modal-summary">Use this process to remove an officer from their position on the WVSDEC for cause. This does not remove their committee membership.</p><div class="key-facts-box"><h4>Key Facts</h4><ul><li><strong>Initiated By:</strong> Written Charges.</li><li><strong>Vote Needed:</strong> 3/5 of voting members.</li><li><strong>Source:</strong> WVSDEC Bylaws, Art. V, Sec. 10(c)</li></ul></div><hr class="modal-divider"><h4>Your Step-by-Step Guide</h4><ol><li><strong>File Written Charges:</strong> **Submit formal written charges** that state the cause for removal.</li><li><strong>Ensure Notice is Sent:</strong> The officer must **receive written notice** at least 15 days before the meeting.</li><li><strong>Attend the Hearing:</strong> At the meeting, the officer **has the right to speak** in their own defense.</li><li><strong>Hold the Vote:</strong> A successful vote requires a 3/5 majority of the committee's voting members.</li></ol><hr class="modal-divider"><h4>What to Expect Next</h4><p>If the motion passes, the office is immediately vacant. The committee will then hold an election to fill the position.</p></div></div></div>
  <div id="modal-dnc-credentials" class="modal" hidden><div class="modal-content"><button class="modal-close" aria-label="Close modal">&times;</button><div class="modal-header"><div class="modal-header-icon">{% image "/images/three-dots-white.svg", "Icon symbolizing a DNC credentials challenge for West Virginia Democrats", { widths: [40, 80], sizes: "40px" } %}</div><h3>Procedure: Filing a DNC Credentials Challenge</h3></div><div class="modal-body"><p class="modal-summary">Use this process to formally challenge the selection of a DNC member from West Virginia.</p><div class="key-facts-box"><h4>Key Facts</h4><ul><li><strong>Filing Deadline:</strong> 30 days from the date the DNC member was selected.</li><li><strong>Who Can File:</strong> Any WV Democrat or any DNC member.</li><li><strong>Source:</strong> DNC Bylaws, Art. Two, Sec. 10(b)</li></ul></div><hr class="modal-divider"><h4>Your Step-by-Step Guide</h4><ol><li><strong>Draft Your Challenge:</strong> Prepare a formal written document outlining the specific reasons for the challenge.</li><li><strong>Send by Registered Mail:</strong> You must **mail the challenge** via Registered Mail (with return receipt) to the DNC Secretary and the Co-Chairs of the DNC Credentials Committee within the 30-day deadline.</li></ol><hr class="modal-divider"><h4>What to Expect Next</h4><p>The DNC Credentials Committee will hear the challenge and provide each party an opportunity to be heard. They will then issue a written report to the full DNC, which makes the final decision.</p></div></div></div>
  <div id="modal-rbc-complaint" class="modal" hidden><div class="modal-content"><button class="modal-close" aria-label="Close modal">&times;</button><div class="modal-header"><div class="modal-header-icon">{% image "/images/three-dots-white.svg", "Icon symbolizing a DNC rules complaint for West Virginia Democrats", { widths: [40, 80], sizes: "40px" } %}</div><h3>Procedure: Filing a DNC Rules Complaint</h3></div><div class="modal-body"><p class="modal-summary">Use this process if state party rules or their implementation violate the DNC Charter and block fair participation.</p><div class="key-facts-box"><h4>Key Facts</h4><ul><li><strong>Prerequisite:</strong> You must have already tried to solve the issue with the state party first.</li><li><strong>Standing:</strong> You must live in the affected area and show real impact from the rule violation.</li><li><strong>Source:</strong> WVSDEC Bylaws, Art. Two, Sec. 11(f)</li></ul></div><hr class="modal-divider"><h4>Your Step-by-Step Guide</h4><ol><li><strong>Exhaust State Remedies:</strong> First, you must **use the state-level appeal process**. Your complaint must include proof you did this or a clear explanation for why it would be pointless.</li><li><strong>Prepare Your Packet:</strong> Assemble a cover letter, a short timeline of events, a list of the specific WVDP and DNC rules that were violated, and all supporting evidence.</li><li><strong>Request a Fix:</strong> Clearly state the practical remedy you are seeking <em>(e.g., order a new meeting with proper notice, require the state party to update a faulty rule)</em>.</li><li><strong>File the Complaint:</strong> Submit your complete packet to the DNC Rules and Bylaws Committee.</li></ol><hr class="modal-divider"><h4>What to Expect Next</h4><p>The DNC committee will review your complaint. This is a high-level process for addressing systemic issues of party fairness and access.</p></div></div></div>
